<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukayshasoulsinger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kaysha Soulsinger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/22/01 1:19:21 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> The best advice I can really give you is to learn by doing. If your healing prowess is not as your group would like it, I'm sure they'll inform you as such <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . Heh, just kidding .. I think you'll learn as you go what is efficient, and what's not.<br>
<br>
You should also remember that while you are there mainly to heal the damage done to your party, there are others who can either prevent that damage (kiting Wizards or Druids, mezzing Enchanters, etc...), or direct that damage a certain way (tanks, mainly).<br>
<br>
As for Complete Healing, it indeed requires a slightly different usage, mainly because of the casting time (10 seconds) and the effect (total heal for target), relative to other healing spells. While it takes a little fine tuning to get this spell under your control, it's not too difficult, I have found myself. I would recommend you try to get the feel for it in a &quot;low risk&quot; situation, when your party is in what I call R&amp;R mode (fighting easy battles, really). Inform your party that you do so, though <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Basically, it's learn as you go ... it's not too hard, really, especially if you have a party in which you know each other. <p><br><A Href="http://www.guildmagic.com/character.cfm?ID=30878"><IMG
SRC="http://members.rott.chello.nl/ldirks/www/KayshaSoulsinger.jpg"></a><BR>
Vicar in the 51th Circle of Erollisi Marr <BR>
<i>The road to Heaven is paved with stones from Hell</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/udalnareklifeinstater.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DalnarekLifeinstater</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>p0\/\/3r-p0sT3r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/22/01 8:52:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> All the above is exactly true.  There is no one all-knowing way to be an upper level cleric.  You learned how to be a low level cleric by trial and error, and you will learn how to progress to the higher levels with practice also.  I cannot add much to Kaysha's statements, as they pretty much describe the transistion from pre-40 to post-40 (the level where things really start to change) cleric. I can only add that you will notice signifigant changes to how you operate in groups at 40, 46, 50 and then pretty much watching yourself fine tune your skill slightly with every level thereafter.  Basically, dont sweat it.  Take controlled chances and see what works and what doesnt. <p><a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=45014">Dalnarek Lifeinstater</a><br>
cleric of <a href="http://www.eqbloodsong.com">Bloodsong</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulashannavalrynn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lashanna Valrynn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/22/01 10:33:32 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://students.washington.edu/zip/eq/lashport.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> I totally agree with all above, but have a few sugestions that might help.  I think the biggest change is that you will now be the primary healer in your group...ie you can't spend 50% of your mana on nukes *in most situations* cuz you will need it to heal.  It of course varries from camp to camp and sit, but as a general rule I think that's the biggest change.  There is also a post on the forums about timing heals...take a look at that. as for CH definatly use it in a low risk sit...I had a higher lvl cleric in my group when i got it and he recomended at 2 reds to start CH...so try it and see what works and see what doesn't...all clerics have different healing styles and you only get that by learning and doing.<br>
<br>
