High Priest of Visions</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucartagia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cartagia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>w4nn4b3!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/27/01 9:59:28 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> I have pretty much learned to stay calm when beaten on.  I've had a lot of experience playing a pure caster to know that running around with your hair on fire never helps.  <br>
<br>
I DIDN'T know the trick about returning to the point where you were knocked back from.  Interesting.  <br>
<br>
I think the biggest challenge I have to learn is in making the hard decision to let someone die.  I think that is the hardest part of being a cleric.  For example, a puller without feign death comes back to the group with 6 fast hitting monsters on him and only 2 bubbles left.   Several times, I've healed the puller anyway, KNOWING that the train would derail on me, but unwilling to give him up.  Sure enough the train derails and I die, leaving the group without a healer.  Shortly after that the enchanter follows, followed by the puller and then the lead tank.  Logically, I know that I shouldn't heal the puller in that situation, but my heart won't let me do it.   <p><BR>
<img src="http://www.kerinakreation.com/images/sigs/cartpic.jpg">
<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ullorianlanys.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Llorian Lanys</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I live here.... get out.</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/28/01 8:39:58 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> That particular situation is one reason its important for clerics to have as high HP / AC as they can get, while keeping their wisdom maxxed.<br>
<br>
Clerics are plate classes for a reason. They are built to take some punishment ( things like lord fleshak not included <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
<br>
If you can get your Hitpoints up, and your Armor Class up, WHEN that train derails on you ( not if, when.. cause its gonna happen sooner or later ), you can stand there and chuckle as the mobs swing vainly on your plate covered butt, and the enchanter mezzes them all.<br>
<br>
 <p><a href="http://www.mithrilweb.com//"target="web"><img src="http://www.mithrilweb.com/images/sigs/llosig.jpg" border="0">

</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uaanniashadowburst.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aannia Shadowburst</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>w4nn4b3!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/28/01 9:58:42 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> You are right about the hardest decision.  In the high end game, the cleric WILL decide who lives and who dies in any given encounter.  Post-51 you will notice your strategy change quite a bit also.  The addition of Celestial Healing and Remedy make it much easier to keep everyone alive.<br>
<br>
I'm sure you already know, but the most important player in a large pull situation (especially raids) will be the enchanters.  I always like to keep the main enchanters hotkeyed with heals on plane raids.  It is also a good idea to keep the main and secondary assist hotkeyed with /target in case their cleric dies.<br>
<br>
As you practice on your way to 60, you will learn what works best for you, but the aspect of multi-group raids will likely be the single largest change in strategy, and possibly the biggest source of frustration for many levels.<br>
<br>
Aannia Shadowburst<br>
54 Vicar<br>
Vita Infinita <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uperplexcerebrum.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Perplex Cerebrum</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://images.honesty.com/imagedata/h/920/44/29204482.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(8/28/01 5:26:00 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://images.honesty.com/imagedata/h/920/44/29204481.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: High Level Game vs. Low Level Game</span><hr size=1> Timing CHs is one of the more important skills you will need to know throughout your career as a cleric. Complete Heal is our class defining spell. Nobody else has it, and nothing else comes close as far as healing efficiency goes. (Well, they say that the res is the most efficient heal used on ranger so that may be exception... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ). <br>
<br>
 If they ever nerf CH or give it to another class, there will be a lot of clerics hanging up their Cat Hats** (tm)  in the corner next to their sprinklers.<br>
<br>
 (** replace with &quot;Pointy Bucket Hats&quot; if dorf, &quot;Alien-ate-my-face Hats&quot; if DE, or &quot;There's-a-pigeon-on-my-head Hats&quot; for human...) <br>
<br>
In comparison, learning CH timing is kind of like learning to ride a bike. The only advice I can give is start using it as soon as you get it and practice. After a while it will become instinctive.<br>
<br>
 You shouldn't really rely on any set rule that tells you when to start CH every time, because that point depends on the damage rate of mob and the HP of your tank. You just gotta get a feel for the damage rate for each type of mob you fight. You will realize how long your tank will live and will know when to fire off that CH so that it lands in time. (or doesn't.... muhahahah!  j/k )<br>
<br>
To learn the craft, I suggest start conservative in every situation, and then push the limits from there. Meaning, up untill you are certain of the damage rate, start your CHs earlier (maybe half HP), then push them further to the left as much as you can while still feeling comfortable about it. This requires that your victim... err, I mean your tank trusts you, and wouldn't get all bent out of shape if something was to go wrong during your learning process. In a controlled environment (1 mob, steady damage rate), you could get it to a point where your CH lands while the tank is in the purple haze. I don't suggest you do that in regular groups, but its good practice as well as a rush for both you and the tank if the tank doesn't mind. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Just start using it asap. Tanks at your level most likely won't have enough HP to make it really efficient and you won't have mana for more than a few per full mana bar, but the experience will be worth it when you get into your 50s.<br>
